00:00:00.840 --> 00:00:04.700
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:22.690 --> 00:00:25.600
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Thank so
much, Gabriel and everyone else

00:00:25.600 --> 00:00:29.190
and Melodias Borinqueñas
for a beautiful concert.

00:00:29.190 --> 00:00:34.440 position:56%
You guys are clearly way up there
in terms of skill level and in terms

00:00:34.440 --> 00:00:37.900
of taste, what you
might call or something.

00:00:37.900 --> 00:00:41.630
Just beauty of every
sort in your performance.

00:00:41.630 --> 00:00:42.930
&gt;&gt; Daniel Muñoz: Thanks so much.

00:00:42.930 --> 00:00:44.230
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Thanks
so much for that.

00:00:44.230 --> 00:00:48.110
Thanks for working for 25 years to
-- just to come here to the Library

00:00:48.110 --> 00:00:50.480
of Congress, this concert today.

00:00:50.480 --> 00:00:51.870
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: I think I
can die in peace after this.

00:00:51.870 --> 00:00:53.170
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: There you go.

00:00:53.170 --> 00:00:55.220
Beautiful, but don't do it.

00:00:55.220 --> 00:01:00.020
So can we start with
who is Gabriel Muñoz?

00:01:00.020 --> 00:01:01.780
Who is that person?

00:01:01.780 --> 00:01:04.150
If you were somebody
else and they asked you

00:01:04.150 --> 00:01:06.600
who Gabriel Muñoz was,
what would you say?

00:01:06.600 --> 00:01:09.860
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: It's
such a complex question,

00:01:09.860 --> 00:01:13.360
but as some of you already know,

00:01:13.360 --> 00:01:16.880
I was born in Hatillo
[spelling?], Puerto Rico.

00:01:16.880 --> 00:01:20.460
I guess to find a better
life, my parents moved

00:01:20.460 --> 00:01:22.550
to New Jersey, where I was raised.

00:01:22.550 --> 00:01:26.880 position:56%
The most difficult question I
always have to answer is how I ended

00:01:26.880 --> 00:01:28.500
up playing this instrument

00:01:28.500 --> 00:01:31.590
and furthermore having a
passion and love for it?

00:01:31.590 --> 00:01:32.890
I have no clue.

00:01:32.890 --> 00:01:34.190
I'll be honest with you.

00:01:34.190 --> 00:01:37.630
Being raised over here
since the age of two,

00:01:37.630 --> 00:01:41.330
it still baffles me how
I ended up doing this.

00:01:41.330 --> 00:01:44.830
I can, however, say that it was --

00:01:44.830 --> 00:01:48.900
basically began with watching
someone play at the age of 14,

00:01:48.900 --> 00:01:55.060
and I've never seen this instrument
in front of me physically,

00:01:55.060 --> 00:01:57.690
only on old cassettes or such

00:01:57.690 --> 00:02:00.420
that my father would play
the old jíbero music,

00:02:00.420 --> 00:02:04.060
and it kind of fascinated me, but
I didn't understand what it was.

00:02:04.060 --> 00:02:06.950
Once I saw it, it enchanted
me instantly.

00:02:06.950 --> 00:02:10.020
I loved the whole chorus
effect, natural chorus effect

00:02:10.020 --> 00:02:13.770
that the instrument had and
how it portrayed itself.

00:02:13.770 --> 00:02:18.900
It just stood out on its own,
and I felt like I really --

00:02:18.900 --> 00:02:21.390
I really want to do that.

00:02:21.390 --> 00:02:23.170
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Well we're all
thankful that you decided that.

00:02:23.170 --> 00:02:25.970
That was a good moment for us.

00:02:25.970 --> 00:02:27.560
You go back to Hatillo
[spelling] at all?

00:02:27.560 --> 00:02:28.860
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Yeah.

00:02:28.860 --> 00:02:31.390
At the age of ten, my Dad
started taking me back

00:02:31.390 --> 00:02:35.680
so that I would know my family,
my grandmother and grandfather

00:02:35.680 --> 00:02:40.450
on his side and such, and every
so often, every couple of years,

00:02:40.450 --> 00:02:43.270
I continued going back until I was
old enough to travel on my own,

00:02:43.270 --> 00:02:45.570
and to this day, I still go.

00:02:45.570 --> 00:02:49.080
Now, I go -- it's at the point
where I go, and it's just meeting

00:02:49.080 --> 00:02:52.890
with different cuartristas and
playing and playing and playing.

00:02:52.890 --> 00:02:54.300
When I get the chance,
I'll see the family,

00:02:54.300 --> 00:02:56.190
but now it's just I'm
always playing now.

00:02:56.190 --> 00:02:59.820
So -- but yeah, it's
always fun to go back

00:02:59.820 --> 00:03:05.190
and recharge my cultural batteries
and musical batteries and meet

00:03:05.190 --> 00:03:07.910
up with a lot of great
musicians over there.

00:03:07.910 --> 00:03:09.210
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Let me ask you.

00:03:09.210 --> 00:03:12.680
Who is on those cassettes
that your father played?

00:03:12.680 --> 00:03:14.630
Do you know at this point in time?

00:03:14.630 --> 00:03:17.330
Who were your -- who would
you go back and meet with?

00:03:17.330 --> 00:03:20.510
Where did you get this -- where
do you recharge your batteries,

00:03:20.510 --> 00:03:21.810
with whom?

00:03:21.810 --> 00:03:25.480
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: I remember my
father playing a lot of cassettes

00:03:25.480 --> 00:03:29.040
from the late great
cuatro player Maso Rivera,

00:03:29.040 --> 00:03:31.020 position:56%
which is one of the biggest pioneers

00:03:31.020 --> 00:03:37.760
on the real typical
folklore music on the cuatro.

00:03:37.760 --> 00:03:40.760
It had such -- I guess I would
interpret it as some type

00:03:40.760 --> 00:03:45.610
of jíbero-funk type feel with it
that really brought out the pride

00:03:45.610 --> 00:03:48.880
of the music in itself,
and that's someone

00:03:48.880 --> 00:03:52.460
that I never had the opportunity
to meet before he passed away

00:03:52.460 --> 00:03:57.340
but till this day one of the
biggest inspirations on --

00:03:57.340 --> 00:04:01.060
the whole reason for me really
wanting to push out on the culture

00:04:01.060 --> 00:04:04.390
with the music was Maso Rivera.

00:04:04.390 --> 00:04:06.140
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Maso Rivera.

00:04:06.140 --> 00:04:08.320
And so what about Ladi
[Ladislao Martínez]

00:04:08.320 --> 00:04:09.820
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Ladi
-- I consider Ladi

00:04:09.820 --> 00:04:12.530
to be the godfather
of the modern cuatro.

00:04:12.530 --> 00:04:16.320
La D is the person who made
the modern cuatro famous,

00:04:16.320 --> 00:04:20.970
the ten strings, the shape, all
this came through evolution.

00:04:20.970 --> 00:04:23.560 position:56%
I understand that cuatro had
different looks throughout the years

00:04:23.560 --> 00:04:30.780
since its creation, but Ladi
deserves so much in my perspective

00:04:30.780 --> 00:04:34.120
so much reverence and
honor for what he did

00:04:34.120 --> 00:04:38.860 position:56%
in modernizing the instrument itself
and style of technique he used

00:04:38.860 --> 00:04:40.570
to play and the music he used.

00:04:40.570 --> 00:04:44.130
He composed so many songs, so
many songs, hundreds of songs

00:04:44.130 --> 00:04:48.670
that until this day are standards
for cuatritas to learn from.

00:04:48.670 --> 00:04:50.900
I can never go without
mentioning Ladi.

00:04:50.900 --> 00:04:54.150
To this day, we still try,
try to learn one or two

00:04:54.150 --> 00:04:55.970
of his songs and perform.

00:04:55.970 --> 00:04:58.650
Like I said, he's the
godfather of the modern cuatro.

00:04:58.650 --> 00:05:01.840
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Well now
that we're on the cuatro,

00:05:01.840 --> 00:05:04.110
tell us about the cuatro.

00:05:04.110 --> 00:05:06.750
For someone who's never seen
the cuatro, doesn't know it.

00:05:06.750 --> 00:05:08.950
Why -- first of all, the ten
strings and it's called cuatro.

00:05:08.950 --> 00:05:10.250
What's that all about?

00:05:10.250 --> 00:05:11.550
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Yeah.

00:05:11.550 --> 00:05:14.340
I mean, there's -- I've heard
so many different stories

00:05:14.340 --> 00:05:16.000
in Puerto Rico and over here

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:20.510
about how the Puerto Rican cuatro
had evolved and has evolved.

00:05:20.510 --> 00:05:23.360
One of the things was
what you just mentioned.

00:05:23.360 --> 00:05:24.660
Why cuatro?

00:05:24.660 --> 00:05:27.400
Cuatro means 'number
four' in Spanish.

00:05:27.400 --> 00:05:32.460
So one of the things I learned
was that it had four strings

00:05:32.460 --> 00:05:35.760
when it first started evolving.

00:05:35.760 --> 00:05:39.830
As time went by, I guess
with different artisans

00:05:39.830 --> 00:05:44.540
and luthiers experimenting, making
instruments, they decided to make

00:05:44.540 --> 00:05:46.990
or add strings, change the shape.

00:05:46.990 --> 00:05:50.120 position:56%
To this day, even in this year 2016,

00:05:50.120 --> 00:05:53.590 position:56%
I see different luthiers
experimenting with different styles,

00:05:53.590 --> 00:05:56.590
shapes and looks -- adding
strings, removing strings.

00:05:56.590 --> 00:06:00.330
A lot of the times it's just a
preference of the musician himself.

00:06:00.330 --> 00:06:05.090
Ladi, for example, he
asked for ten strings.

00:06:05.090 --> 00:06:07.540
There's another cuatrita
by the name of --

00:06:07.540 --> 00:06:09.620
known as Totas Feliciano
[spelling?].

00:06:09.620 --> 00:06:11.980
He was one of the original pioneers

00:06:11.980 --> 00:06:15.410
of where the cuatro hadn't even
evolved yet, had four strings,

00:06:15.410 --> 00:06:19.220
six strings, eight strings, and as
these guys went along, they added,

00:06:19.220 --> 00:06:24.270
modified - but Ladi really made the
ten-string popular, the violin look

00:06:24.270 --> 00:06:26.130
with the ten strings was the
modern cuatro that Ladi made.

00:06:26.130 --> 00:06:29.340
&gt;&gt;Daniel Sheehy: The
violin look, with the...

00:06:29.340 --> 00:06:30.640
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Yeah.

00:06:30.640 --> 00:06:34.360
The violin with the -- as
European music influenced a lot

00:06:34.360 --> 00:06:41.280 position:56%
in Puerto Rico, the jíbaro, as we
call [him] wanted to feel some sense

00:06:41.280 --> 00:06:47.200
of sophistication, some sense of
acceptance in the higher class,

00:06:47.200 --> 00:06:49.810
and they kind of copied
the violin shape

00:06:49.810 --> 00:06:53.950
since that represented the violin,
a lot of the classical music

00:06:53.950 --> 00:06:59.870
and modern style, higher class
music and so the countrymen,

00:06:59.870 --> 00:07:07.110
the peasant of Puerto Rico thought,
"hey, that shape signifies this."

00:07:07.110 --> 00:07:10.330
And they wanted to add to
that so they figured that's

00:07:10.330 --> 00:07:14.140
where Ladi made this famous with
the modern Puerto Rican cuatro.

00:07:14.140 --> 00:07:15.550
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: So,
as far as you know.

00:07:15.550 --> 00:07:20.940 position:56%
Ladi was the one who really made
that the standard, that shape there?

00:07:20.940 --> 00:07:24.280 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Yeah, once -- I
can't tell you he specifically asked

00:07:24.280 --> 00:07:28.330
for this shape, but I
do know that once Ladi -

00:07:28.330 --> 00:07:34.930
Ladi Martinez is his full name
- once Ladi started coming

00:07:34.930 --> 00:07:38.860
out on the radio performing live,

00:07:38.860 --> 00:07:40.290
people would hear him
all over the island.

00:07:40.290 --> 00:07:44.380
He was one of the first ones to
come out on the air performing.

00:07:44.380 --> 00:07:47.660
Everyone around the island wanted
to know what was that cuatro,

00:07:47.660 --> 00:07:49.990
that instrument he was playing.

00:07:49.990 --> 00:07:53.140
Once they saw it, everyone's
baffled, and it just kind

00:07:53.140 --> 00:07:55.330
of took off like wild fire.

00:07:55.330 --> 00:07:58.290
Everyone ordering cuatros
made the same way,

00:07:58.290 --> 00:08:01.640
and it became the standard
cuatro after Ladi.

00:08:01.640 --> 00:08:05.020
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: And I think
didn't he have two cuatros

00:08:05.020 --> 00:08:06.820
in his ensembles?

00:08:06.820 --> 00:08:08.120
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Yeah.

00:08:08.120 --> 00:08:11.270
It was Ladi and he had a
cousin named Sarrail Archilla,

00:08:11.270 --> 00:08:13.520
if I'm not mistaken,
one of his own cousins

00:08:13.520 --> 00:08:16.230
that would play harmony
to his songs....

00:08:16.230 --> 00:08:17.530
&gt;&gt; Anibal Ortiz: Duo?

00:08:17.530 --> 00:08:18.830
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: His duo,
yeah, to all his pieces.

00:08:18.830 --> 00:08:20.500
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Do you
ever do that yourself or --

00:08:20.500 --> 00:08:22.650
you had one cuatro [inaudible]?

00:08:22.650 --> 00:08:23.950
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Yeah.

00:08:23.950 --> 00:08:25.930
We predominantly tend
to have the one cuatro,

00:08:25.930 --> 00:08:27.930
but once in a while
we'll get together

00:08:27.930 --> 00:08:32.520
with another fellow cuatro player
and try to work on a double -

00:08:32.520 --> 00:08:34.540
two-part piece or something.

00:08:34.540 --> 00:08:36.400
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: What
are the advantages

00:08:36.400 --> 00:08:39.480
of having just one cuatro?

00:08:39.480 --> 00:08:41.900
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: I guess you
have more room to improvise

00:08:41.900 --> 00:08:45.350
and to just have fun and let go,
sort of like what I do on stage.

00:08:45.350 --> 00:08:50.690
When you have two cuatros
and you have to kind of try

00:08:50.690 --> 00:08:55.010
to stay organized section just to
harmonize with the second cuatro.

00:08:55.010 --> 00:08:58.680
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: So we're talking
about the cuatro [inaudible].

00:08:58.680 --> 00:09:01.210
Can you just give a
little sound or tell us --

00:09:01.210 --> 00:09:03.980
people who might not have heard
this before or close up like this?

00:09:03.980 --> 00:09:05.790
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Yeah,
well what I love

00:09:05.790 --> 00:09:11.010
about this instrument also I
consider the 12-string guitar,

00:09:11.010 --> 00:09:13.810
the American guitar,
12 steel string.

00:09:13.810 --> 00:09:16.330
It has -- being that
the strings are doubled,

00:09:16.330 --> 00:09:21.100
it kind of gives a
natural chorus effect.

00:09:21.100 --> 00:09:24.470
You see a lot of rock guitars
and such that will plug

00:09:24.470 --> 00:09:27.640
up to an amplifier, let's
say, or an effects pedal,

00:09:27.640 --> 00:09:30.740
and it'll add a chorus effect.

00:09:30.740 --> 00:09:33.540
This has a natural --
a chorus effect just

00:09:33.540 --> 00:09:36.030
by having the double strings
as also the 12-string guitar,

00:09:36.030 --> 00:09:39.370
which is something
that just fascinates me

00:09:39.370 --> 00:09:44.200
and so this is what it sounds like.

00:09:44.200 --> 00:09:48.090
[Plays a chord.] So
it's difficult to tell,

00:09:48.090 --> 00:09:53.830
but if you have the patience
and the ear to listen to it,

00:09:53.830 --> 00:09:57.180
the waves kind sort of -- the
sound waves sort of go like this,

00:09:57.180 --> 00:10:00.310
and you can kind of feel
that vibration as opposed

00:10:00.310 --> 00:10:02.250
to a single string -- if I were
to play [plays single string]--

00:10:02.250 --> 00:10:05.950
if I'm playing the double,

00:10:05.950 --> 00:10:10.700
it has sort of a more
robust or fuller sound.

00:10:10.700 --> 00:10:15.170
And that's something that always
stuck in my ear when I would watch

00:10:15.170 --> 00:10:18.330
or listen to anyone play.

00:10:18.330 --> 00:10:20.550
My thing is to listen
to their technique.

00:10:20.550 --> 00:10:23.290
How do they use that
to their advantage?

00:10:23.290 --> 00:10:26.490
And that kind of resonates
with me the most.

00:10:26.490 --> 00:10:29.700
One of which is Edwin Colón Zayas

00:10:29.700 --> 00:10:34.310
that has practically dominated
almost every genre that exists

00:10:34.310 --> 00:10:36.160
for the Puerto Rican cuatro.

00:10:36.160 --> 00:10:38.360
His technique is beyond phenomenal.

00:10:38.360 --> 00:10:41.750 position:56%
And that's something that I always
pay attention to when I watch people

00:10:41.750 --> 00:10:43.050
and listen to people play.

00:10:43.050 --> 00:10:45.750
How do they use that to
their advantage, of course,

00:10:45.750 --> 00:10:47.050
using their own technique.

00:10:47.050 --> 00:10:50.020
Every musician developed
their own style and technique.

00:10:50.020 --> 00:10:54.770
And Edwin has kind of
dominated every part

00:10:54.770 --> 00:10:56.660
of the cuatro to this day.

00:10:56.660 --> 00:11:00.340 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: When you play the
Bach, for some reason my mind jumped

00:11:00.340 --> 00:11:02.620
to his version of "The
Flight of the Bumble Bee."

00:11:02.620 --> 00:11:03.920
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Yes.

00:11:03.920 --> 00:11:06.260
Yes. Exactly.

00:11:06.260 --> 00:11:11.210 position:56%
Like I said, he's kind of dominated
everything since the 80s, I believe.

00:11:11.210 --> 00:11:14.370
Edwin has been tinkering
with classical music,

00:11:14.370 --> 00:11:17.390 position:56%
and every time he puts an album
out, there's always a classical song

00:11:17.390 --> 00:11:22.340
in there, one or two, and it's
just his way of saying, hey,

00:11:22.340 --> 00:11:27.060 position:56%
the Puerto Rican cuatro can be
mainstream, it can be used for this.

00:11:27.060 --> 00:11:29.170
It's inspiring the rest of us.

00:11:29.170 --> 00:11:30.470
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: What's
your message

00:11:30.470 --> 00:11:34.480
when you include a Bach
Suite, for example, cello?

00:11:34.480 --> 00:11:37.440
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Basically, I
would say I'm kind of going off

00:11:37.440 --> 00:11:44.530
of what Edwin and several
other cuatro players have done.

00:11:44.530 --> 00:11:48.500
I don't like to keep the
cuatro inside this box

00:11:48.500 --> 00:11:53.090 position:56%
where it's predominantly just
mountain music, using Christmas time

00:11:53.090 --> 00:11:57.950
for like what we consider Christmas
caroling, what we know as parandas

00:11:57.950 --> 00:12:01.200
and it's just jamming,
and we're going house

00:12:01.200 --> 00:12:03.360
to house Christmas caroling and
that's it the rest of the year

00:12:03.360 --> 00:12:07.190 position:56%
because this instrument is basically
most popular at Christmas time.

00:12:07.190 --> 00:12:10.030
But I like where a lot
of cuatritas are going,

00:12:10.030 --> 00:12:11.590
where they're just
taking it out of that box

00:12:11.590 --> 00:12:14.390
and say here, there's
some bluegrass.

00:12:14.390 --> 00:12:16.400
Here's some R and B.
Here's some classical.

00:12:16.400 --> 00:12:17.850
Here's this, here's that.

00:12:17.850 --> 00:12:20.360
And I kind of like the
idea and the concept

00:12:20.360 --> 00:12:24.010
of making it a little bit more
mainstream because I feel,

00:12:24.010 --> 00:12:26.080
obviously, it'll reach
more cultures, more people

00:12:26.080 --> 00:12:28.580
and say hey here's
this instrument just

00:12:28.580 --> 00:12:30.900
in case you didn't know it existed.

00:12:30.900 --> 00:12:33.360
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: You lived in New
Jersey for a long time now, right?

00:12:33.360 --> 00:12:34.880
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Yes, sir.

00:12:34.880 --> 00:12:37.350
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Yomo
Toro, you run across him?

00:12:37.350 --> 00:12:39.280
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: I
had the opportunity

00:12:39.280 --> 00:12:41.700
of meeting him on two occasions.

00:12:41.700 --> 00:12:46.520
He did -- he frequented New Jersey
a lot, and he did come to my area

00:12:46.520 --> 00:12:49.910
in Trenton where I reside,
to perform on two occasions.

00:12:49.910 --> 00:12:52.150
I had the -- I didn't have the
privilege and honor of performing

00:12:52.150 --> 00:12:55.050
with him, but I got to
sit and watch this great,

00:12:55.050 --> 00:12:57.300
great legend and master perform.

00:12:57.300 --> 00:12:58.600
I'll be honest with you.

00:12:58.600 --> 00:13:00.540
I wouldn't want to
even take my instrument

00:13:00.540 --> 00:13:02.210
out of the case in front of him.

00:13:02.210 --> 00:13:05.200
I mean, it's just I
honored him so much.

00:13:05.200 --> 00:13:10.230
He's always another inspiration
with his style and genre tapping

00:13:10.230 --> 00:13:16.820 position:56%
into the salsa world, something that
I believe he made popular with a lot

00:13:16.820 --> 00:13:20.980
of old school salsa singers,
Celia Cruz, Willie Colon

00:13:20.980 --> 00:13:24.600
and La Fania All Stars Group
that was formed in the 70s.

00:13:24.600 --> 00:13:29.220
I remember the story
of him being requested

00:13:29.220 --> 00:13:31.900
at the recording studio
for a salsa album.

00:13:31.900 --> 00:13:33.700
They told him bring
the electric guitar.

00:13:33.700 --> 00:13:36.650 position:56%
Bring your friend or we're going to
put some rock guitar into the salsa.

00:13:36.650 --> 00:13:38.650
Give it some kind of fusion.

00:13:38.650 --> 00:13:42.280
The day comes to record, and
Yomo shows up at the studio

00:13:42.280 --> 00:13:44.660
with his cuatro on his back.

00:13:44.660 --> 00:13:47.580
And Willie Colon, one of the
producers of the album said,

00:13:47.580 --> 00:13:49.000
"We're not recording
Christmas music.

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:51.670
This isn't jíbaro music
from the mountains."

00:13:51.670 --> 00:13:53.230 position:56%
And Yomo says, "I'm a cuatro player.

00:13:53.230 --> 00:13:54.530
This is what I play."

00:13:54.530 --> 00:13:55.830
The rest was history.

00:13:55.830 --> 00:13:57.520
He made that popular
everywhere he went.

00:13:57.520 --> 00:14:00.110
I mean, they traveled the world,
Africa, Japan, you name it.

00:14:00.110 --> 00:14:03.860 position:56%
And the cuatro was front and center
with that, and it's people like that

00:14:03.860 --> 00:14:05.960
that we have to give thanks to,

00:14:05.960 --> 00:14:09.560
younger generation
of cuatro players.

00:14:09.560 --> 00:14:11.930
We know that there's that
opportunity out there.

00:14:11.930 --> 00:14:13.530
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: That's
a good topic right there.

00:14:13.530 --> 00:14:16.100
Can you tell us -- I mean,
you're in circulation.

00:14:16.100 --> 00:14:17.400
You go around and hear
different groups

00:14:17.400 --> 00:14:19.590
and they hear you,
and you meet people.

00:14:19.590 --> 00:14:23.580
What is happening with the
younger generation and the cuatro?

00:14:23.580 --> 00:14:29.900 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: I'm kind of on the
fence on the growth of the cuatro.

00:14:29.900 --> 00:14:33.610
I obviously see more
popularity of the cuatro

00:14:33.610 --> 00:14:36.690
on the island, in Puerto Rico.

00:14:36.690 --> 00:14:39.470
There's -- schools are
starting to make it part

00:14:39.470 --> 00:14:41.320
of the curriculum now
to learn the cuatro.

00:14:41.320 --> 00:14:46.380
There's a young man by the
name of Pablo Hernandez.

00:14:46.380 --> 00:14:49.950
He's the first in history to
graduate with a Bachelor degree --

00:14:49.950 --> 00:14:53.490
Bachelor's degree on the Puerto
Rican cuatro with a concentration

00:14:53.490 --> 00:14:57.810
in jazz, just a month ago in
Puerto Rico, and they're starting

00:14:57.810 --> 00:15:01.760 position:56%
to make it a curriculum now which
is something I'm very proud to know,

00:15:01.760 --> 00:15:04.010
and I'm glad to be
alive during this time

00:15:04.010 --> 00:15:06.040
where this is coming into fruition.

00:15:06.040 --> 00:15:10.480
I wish that over here in the States
more younger people would get

00:15:10.480 --> 00:15:13.430
involved not necessarily just
learning to play the instrument,

00:15:13.430 --> 00:15:17.280
but at least learn about it and
learn the culture and be involved

00:15:17.280 --> 00:15:22.090
with it so that we can pass this
heritage down to our children.

00:15:22.090 --> 00:15:23.550
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: New
Jersey and New York,

00:15:23.550 --> 00:15:26.900
I think have probably been
important places for the cuatro

00:15:26.900 --> 00:15:31.380
and jíbaro ever since Ladi
was around there, right?

00:15:31.380 --> 00:15:34.680
It was a major hit
and galvanized people

00:15:34.680 --> 00:15:41.300
and raised their Puerto Rican sense
of self, identity and dignity.

00:15:41.300 --> 00:15:46.400
Do you have -- say you
want to renew your roots.

00:15:46.400 --> 00:15:48.720
Are there people in New
Jersey, New York, Hartford,

00:15:48.720 --> 00:15:50.020
Connecticut, Chicago or --

00:15:50.020 --> 00:15:51.320
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Yeah.

00:15:51.320 --> 00:15:52.620
There's quite a few.

00:15:52.620 --> 00:15:53.920
They're sparse but
there's quite a few.

00:15:53.920 --> 00:15:59.480
There's a small community, and
I try my best to try to network

00:15:59.480 --> 00:16:03.500
with as many as I can to
keep it going, share music.

00:16:03.500 --> 00:16:05.260
We sit down and "Hey,
you teach me this song.

00:16:05.260 --> 00:16:06.560
I'll teach you that song.

00:16:06.560 --> 00:16:07.860
You teach me this riff.

00:16:07.860 --> 00:16:09.160
I'll teach you that riff."

00:16:09.160 --> 00:16:10.460
Just to stay inspired.

00:16:10.460 --> 00:16:12.540
It also keeps you motivated
when you're surrounded

00:16:12.540 --> 00:16:15.790
by that type of atmosphere.

00:16:15.790 --> 00:16:19.810
You as a musician -- everyone
gets an inspiration, a motivation,

00:16:19.810 --> 00:16:23.460
an idea, a thought from
someone else or somewhere else,

00:16:23.460 --> 00:16:28.510
so we try to always keep a close
knit relationship with a lot

00:16:28.510 --> 00:16:29.810
of -- especially New York.

00:16:29.810 --> 00:16:34.010 position:56%
New York is, I believe, is really
crowded with a lot of cuatro players

00:16:34.010 --> 00:16:36.820
and people that are involved
somehow directly or indirectly

00:16:36.820 --> 00:16:38.770
with the music of the
Puerto Rican cuatro.

00:16:38.770 --> 00:16:42.630
So we try to reach out to
as many as we possibly can.

00:16:42.630 --> 00:16:43.930
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Let me ask you.

00:16:43.930 --> 00:16:48.070 position:56%
This is a little bit of an
abstract question, but you've played

00:16:48.070 --> 00:16:51.730
and learned in Puerto Rico,
and you've played and learned

00:16:51.730 --> 00:16:54.820
in New Jersey and New
York, around there.

00:16:54.820 --> 00:16:56.120
How is it different?

00:16:56.120 --> 00:16:57.420
Is it different?

00:16:57.420 --> 00:16:59.480
Is there a different
feeling or different music?

00:16:59.480 --> 00:17:00.780
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Yeah, there is.

00:17:00.780 --> 00:17:04.460
We actually talk about that a lot.

00:17:04.460 --> 00:17:07.530
The styles and techniques
are a bit different.

00:17:07.530 --> 00:17:13.700
Melodies are a bit different in
Puerto Rico then it is over here.

00:17:13.700 --> 00:17:21.210
Being raised over here, my
influences would be Jimmy Hendrix,

00:17:21.210 --> 00:17:25.410
things more popular over here;
whereas over there they live,

00:17:25.410 --> 00:17:29.330
eat and breathe this
instrument 24/7 and everyone

00:17:29.330 --> 00:17:31.000
that has played before them.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:34.300
So they're what I would like
to consider much more hard core

00:17:34.300 --> 00:17:36.420
when it comes to the
cuatro, and I hear it.

00:17:36.420 --> 00:17:40.420
I'm like they have such a
wonderful flavor to their music,

00:17:40.420 --> 00:17:44.060
such a wonderful flavor that
we try to imitate to the best

00:17:44.060 --> 00:17:46.910
of our ability being
that we're over here.

00:17:46.910 --> 00:17:49.790
We have the privilege and honor
of having good rapport with a lot

00:17:49.790 --> 00:17:52.260
of musicians in Puerto Rico.

00:17:52.260 --> 00:17:56.420
And so they have no problem with
sharing with us anytime we call

00:17:56.420 --> 00:17:59.800
or share videos or
phone calls and ideas.

00:17:59.800 --> 00:18:01.960
"Hey, you did something
on this video that I saw.

00:18:01.960 --> 00:18:03.260
You played this song.

00:18:03.260 --> 00:18:04.560
How do you do that?"

00:18:04.560 --> 00:18:06.190
And we have no problem sharing.

00:18:06.190 --> 00:18:07.490
"Say, hey, listen.

00:18:07.490 --> 00:18:08.790
I'm going to send you the music.

00:18:08.790 --> 00:18:10.090
I'll send you the video.

00:18:10.090 --> 00:18:11.390
Just grab your cuatro.

00:18:11.390 --> 00:18:12.690
We'll be over the phone.

00:18:12.690 --> 00:18:13.990
We'll just do it over the phone."

00:18:13.990 --> 00:18:15.290
So we have that advantage.

00:18:15.290 --> 00:18:17.100
But yeah, the sound's
a little bit different.

00:18:17.100 --> 00:18:18.880
The techniques are a
little bit different

00:18:18.880 --> 00:18:20.730
from over here and over there.

00:18:20.730 --> 00:18:25.380
But generally, cuatro players
and also guitar players

00:18:25.380 --> 00:18:29.840
that accompany the cuatro
for the most part try

00:18:29.840 --> 00:18:34.280
to imitate whatever we can from
the island, which is more pure.

00:18:34.280 --> 00:18:38.560
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: They borrowed a
bit, though, in Puerto Rico, right?

00:18:38.560 --> 00:18:42.630
Like from the joropo from
Venezuela or Colombia?

00:18:42.630 --> 00:18:43.930
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Yeah.

00:18:43.930 --> 00:18:45.230
There's a major --

00:18:45.230 --> 00:18:46.530
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: You
got [inaudible].

00:18:46.530 --> 00:18:47.830
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: There's so
many influences in Puerto Rico.

00:18:47.830 --> 00:18:49.130
There's so much to grab from.

00:18:49.130 --> 00:18:51.110
There's so much to grab from with
the pasida [spelling?], the joropo,

00:18:51.110 --> 00:18:57.640 position:56%
the valse, the paso doble, the
mazurka, what we interpret it today.

00:18:57.640 --> 00:19:00.160
There is so much to grab for, and
there's a little bit of influence,

00:19:00.160 --> 00:19:03.460 position:56%
so much, so many different countries
in South America in different areas,

00:19:03.460 --> 00:19:08.750
and this kind of evolved
into this wonderful thing

00:19:08.750 --> 00:19:12.830
where we feel we can make
it our own for the cuatro,

00:19:12.830 --> 00:19:15.150
and like I mentioned earlier,

00:19:15.150 --> 00:19:20.290
we like to consider the
dansa sort of classical form.

00:19:20.290 --> 00:19:23.780
To me, it's one of the
higher end class of music,

00:19:23.780 --> 00:19:27.250
sort of like ballroom dancing and
stuff like that, and the same thing

00:19:27.250 --> 00:19:29.760
with the valse and the mazurka .

00:19:29.760 --> 00:19:34.020
These are styles and genres
of music that, I really feel,

00:19:34.020 --> 00:19:37.660
you have to put your pants on
right and learn them properly

00:19:37.660 --> 00:19:39.070
and interpret them right.

00:19:39.070 --> 00:19:43.210
Before or after our performance
today, I was approached by a woman

00:19:43.210 --> 00:19:45.600
that said "I'm a classical
guitarist,

00:19:45.600 --> 00:19:49.230
and I saw you play this classical
piece," and she was complimenting.

00:19:49.230 --> 00:19:50.530
And I said, "You know what?

00:19:50.530 --> 00:19:52.240
Thank you for telling me that
now and not before I played.

00:19:52.240 --> 00:19:54.970
I would have felt so much
more pressure knowing

00:19:54.970 --> 00:19:59.310
that there's an actual classical
guitarist in the midst."

00:19:59.310 --> 00:20:03.610
So it's those styles of music
that we take from every country

00:20:03.610 --> 00:20:07.260
and have become our own throughout
the years because of people

00:20:07.260 --> 00:20:10.530
like Ladi, because of people
like Maso or Yomo Toro

00:20:10.530 --> 00:20:13.550
and these cuatro players
of the old guard

00:20:13.550 --> 00:20:16.970
that have made those
standards for us.

00:20:16.970 --> 00:20:19.510
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: At some point,
we should turn to the music.

00:20:19.510 --> 00:20:22.190
I had one other -- just
to continue on the --

00:20:22.190 --> 00:20:24.210
what the cuatro means to you:

00:20:24.210 --> 00:20:28.140
When you were explaining
how you play a string,

00:20:28.140 --> 00:20:31.990
and there's that double little
bit of a vibration that's created

00:20:31.990 --> 00:20:35.180
by the two almost the same pitches.

00:20:35.180 --> 00:20:37.670
Also it's against your
body, and I'll just --

00:20:37.670 --> 00:20:38.970
my own impression when you're

00:20:38.970 --> 00:20:42.910
on the stage performing
you're really in yourself.

00:20:42.910 --> 00:20:44.370
You're in a world there.

00:20:44.370 --> 00:20:47.890
Can you either remember
a time before

00:20:47.890 --> 00:20:53.810 position:56%
where you suddenly felt really
moved or what -- tell us about that.

00:20:53.810 --> 00:20:55.110
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Yeah.

00:20:55.110 --> 00:20:58.030
I guess I try to focus
and concentrate

00:20:58.030 --> 00:21:01.860
on my most intimate
moments with the instrument.

00:21:01.860 --> 00:21:05.040
It's so simple for us
as instrumentalists

00:21:05.040 --> 00:21:08.320
of any instrument whether it's
the cuatro guitar, piano, violin,

00:21:08.320 --> 00:21:10.100
clarinet, doesn't matter.

00:21:10.100 --> 00:21:14.780
We are -- or even vocal singer --
we do our best when we're alone,

00:21:14.780 --> 00:21:16.470
when we're in private
when no one's watching.

00:21:16.470 --> 00:21:17.770
There's no pressure.

00:21:17.770 --> 00:21:19.270
Even in the shower.

00:21:19.270 --> 00:21:20.570
I sing better in the shower.

00:21:20.570 --> 00:21:23.050
You'll never hear me
in public, for example.

00:21:23.050 --> 00:21:28.160
So I try to zone in and hone
in on those moments in my mind

00:21:28.160 --> 00:21:33.030 position:56%
and in my emotions while I'm
playing of the most intimate moments

00:21:33.030 --> 00:21:37.160
so that it will, I guess level
my comfort zone to try to focus

00:21:37.160 --> 00:21:39.170
on my mission, which is to try

00:21:39.170 --> 00:21:42.160
to make you feel what I'm feeling
while I'm playing which is to try

00:21:42.160 --> 00:21:45.490
to make you think about where
I'm taking you through my music

00:21:45.490 --> 00:21:47.600
and why and when and where.

00:21:47.600 --> 00:21:52.980
And I feel that it'll resonate more
with your memory and your heart

00:21:52.980 --> 00:21:55.210
that you walk away
with an experience

00:21:55.210 --> 00:21:57.070
and not just entertainment.

00:21:57.070 --> 00:22:03.410
And so when I perform, my
ultimate goal essentially is

00:22:03.410 --> 00:22:05.120
to do just that exactly.

00:22:05.120 --> 00:22:10.420
Just try to resonate my thoughts,
feelings, emotions at that moment.

00:22:10.420 --> 00:22:13.430
And again, I zone into those
intimate moments when I'm

00:22:13.430 --> 00:22:16.920
in my room, for example, my
bedroom either composing a piece

00:22:16.920 --> 00:22:20.010
or just playing something I've
played a thousand times before.

00:22:20.010 --> 00:22:22.860 position:56%
Did I play it differently this time?

00:22:22.860 --> 00:22:24.160
Did you understand it?

00:22:24.160 --> 00:22:25.460
Did you appreciate it?

00:22:25.460 --> 00:22:26.760
Why and how?

00:22:26.760 --> 00:22:29.160
Because those are the type of
moments that resonate with me

00:22:29.160 --> 00:22:31.030
with other cuatro players.

00:22:31.030 --> 00:22:32.330
I walk away with an experience.

00:22:32.330 --> 00:22:35.350 position:56%
I remember that more than just being
entertained, just putting on a show.

00:22:35.350 --> 00:22:37.850
I can talk to him here
over their playing,

00:22:37.850 --> 00:22:39.150
but you're not doing anything.

00:22:39.150 --> 00:22:40.450
It's just entertainment.

00:22:40.450 --> 00:22:43.720
But when you have my full
complete focus on you,

00:22:43.720 --> 00:22:46.290
it's because you're doing
something through the instrument

00:22:46.290 --> 00:22:50.070
and so that's what
ultimately my goal is.

00:22:50.070 --> 00:22:51.370
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Do you --

00:22:51.370 --> 00:22:53.700
are those feelings different
when you play in Puerto Rico then

00:22:53.700 --> 00:22:56.610
when you play in New
Jersey or New York or...

00:22:56.610 --> 00:22:57.910
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Yeah.

00:22:57.910 --> 00:22:59.390
When I have -- I have to admit.

00:22:59.390 --> 00:23:03.230
When we're visiting the island,
it's such a different spirit

00:23:03.230 --> 00:23:06.430
that just comes over us when we're
playing, specifically when we meet

00:23:06.430 --> 00:23:11.470
up with other cuatritas or
guitarists that are known for this

00:23:11.470 --> 00:23:14.960 position:56%
because you're trying to exactly
emotionally connect with that person

00:23:14.960 --> 00:23:18.080
and so when we're back here,
back home in the States,

00:23:18.080 --> 00:23:24.050
we're trying to re-enact that,
if you will, and we try to live

00:23:24.050 --> 00:23:29.360
that moment that we had in front of
you here so that you can try to get

00:23:29.360 --> 00:23:33.660
that interpretation of what it
is we're doing in Puerto Rico,

00:23:33.660 --> 00:23:37.200
what the music is doing over there.

00:23:37.200 --> 00:23:40.770
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Turning
to the music a bit here.

00:23:40.770 --> 00:23:44.340
You mentioned the aguinaldo
genre as the bedrock

00:23:44.340 --> 00:23:48.450
of some of things you play here.

00:23:48.450 --> 00:23:51.360
Tell us about some of the
other genres, valse and dansa

00:23:51.360 --> 00:23:52.790
and those kinds of things.

00:23:52.790 --> 00:23:55.340
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: As I said
prior, the dansa is one

00:23:55.340 --> 00:24:01.090
of the most beautiful, beautiful
forms that exists for the cuatro.

00:24:01.090 --> 00:24:05.500 position:56%
My dream is to eventually record an
album where it's nothing but dansas.

00:24:05.500 --> 00:24:08.270
One of the most beautiful
things ever heard

00:24:08.270 --> 00:24:09.900
on the Puerto Rican cuatro.

00:24:09.900 --> 00:24:13.740
It wasn't originally the dansa
particularly wasn't originally

00:24:13.740 --> 00:24:16.050
created for the cuatro,
by the cuatro.

00:24:16.050 --> 00:24:21.220 position:56%
It was an orchestra type arrangement
played on piano and horns and such.

00:24:21.220 --> 00:24:25.170
But as time went by and the cuatro
started becoming more mainstream

00:24:25.170 --> 00:24:30.850
in the late 1800s and things
like that, early 1900s,

00:24:30.850 --> 00:24:33.870
and what Ladi did do it, for
example, I'll go back to that.

00:24:33.870 --> 00:24:36.560
The dansa became more
and more and more.

00:24:36.560 --> 00:24:39.550
And such -- the same thing
with the valse, the same thing

00:24:39.550 --> 00:24:43.250
with the mazurka, the same
thing with the joropo.

00:24:43.250 --> 00:24:45.850
Each style is in its own
world but still stands

00:24:45.850 --> 00:24:48.960
out in its own form of class.

00:24:48.960 --> 00:24:51.500
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Could you
introduce your colleague

00:24:51.500 --> 00:24:55.970
and maybe give us a taste of
alguinaldo and then a seis or two

00:24:55.970 --> 00:24:58.490
and then maybe a dansa,
whatever you're moved to --

00:24:58.490 --> 00:24:59.790
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Yeah.

00:24:59.790 --> 00:25:03.290
This is Anibal Ortiz,
our group guitarist.

00:25:03.290 --> 00:25:07.540
We've been playing together for
approximately ten years now.

00:25:07.540 --> 00:25:11.640
And the moment we started
playing we instantly clicked.

00:25:11.640 --> 00:25:14.580
Being that Anibal also plays
a little bit of cuatro,

00:25:14.580 --> 00:25:16.430
so he's familiar with the style.

00:25:16.430 --> 00:25:20.350
He has that in his ear already,
which he translates to the guitar

00:25:20.350 --> 00:25:25.850
and I believe perfect
accompaniment on many instances.

00:25:25.850 --> 00:25:28.090 position:56%
And yeah, we would love to try to go

00:25:28.090 --> 00:25:29.760
through maybe a couple
of different --

00:25:29.760 --> 00:25:31.390
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Yeah, just a
little taste, a little sample.

00:25:31.390 --> 00:25:32.690
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: A couple genres.

00:25:32.690 --> 00:25:34.260
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Gives a
sense of how they're different.

00:25:34.260 --> 00:25:35.560
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Yeah.

00:25:35.560 --> 00:25:40.280
So here we'll do the alguinaldo
"Auro Que Venyo" [spelling?]

00:25:40.280 --> 00:25:43.380
and it basically goes like -- which
is like you said earlier is sort

