I don't fabricate numbers,
mass fabrication.

00:40:44.030 --> 00:40:47.000
I work on two, maybe
three an entire year."

00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:49.290
That way he puts all his heart
and soul into it in detail.

00:40:49.290 --> 00:40:53.840
And six months turned into a
year, and it was finally done.

00:40:53.840 --> 00:40:57.200
He took his time, and I was more
than content, more than happy

00:40:57.200 --> 00:40:58.500
when I opened the case and saw it.

00:40:58.500 --> 00:40:59.800
That's another thing.

00:40:59.800 --> 00:41:01.180
I don't know what I'm going to get.

00:41:01.180 --> 00:41:02.480
I'm over here.

00:41:02.480 --> 00:41:04.210
It's different if I'm over there
with him, and I can say okay,

00:41:04.210 --> 00:41:06.080
this is how I want it to look.

00:41:06.080 --> 00:41:07.380
I want that wood.

00:41:07.380 --> 00:41:08.680
I want this sound.

00:41:08.680 --> 00:41:11.070
But I didn't know what I was going
to get until I opened the case.

00:41:11.070 --> 00:41:12.370
And I feel in love with it.

00:41:12.370 --> 00:41:14.040
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Is that
cedar, mahogany or what is that?

00:41:14.040 --> 00:41:15.340
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: What's
that -- the back?

00:41:15.340 --> 00:41:16.640
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: This side.

00:41:16.640 --> 00:41:17.940
This side, yeah.

00:41:17.940 --> 00:41:19.240
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: The side
-- this is actually rosewood.

00:41:19.240 --> 00:41:20.540
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Rosewood?

00:41:20.540 --> 00:41:21.840
Okay.

00:41:21.840 --> 00:41:23.140
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Yeah.

00:41:23.140 --> 00:41:24.440
This is --

00:41:24.440 --> 00:41:25.740
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: So
that's your request, right?

00:41:25.740 --> 00:41:27.040
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Yeah.

00:41:27.040 --> 00:41:28.340
Rosewood -- Brazilian rosewood,
which was aged for 20 years.

00:41:28.340 --> 00:41:31.190
And I think an English spruce
top, was aged for ten years.

00:41:31.190 --> 00:41:35.890
And so everything that he does
it's climate controlled wood,

00:41:35.890 --> 00:41:38.090
climate controlled
work that he does,

00:41:38.090 --> 00:41:41.200
aged so that you get a
good quality instrument.

00:41:41.200 --> 00:41:43.480
Not a lot of people are doing that.

00:41:43.480 --> 00:41:44.980
Yeah, the arm rest also.

00:41:44.980 --> 00:41:46.590
This is a nice little detail.

00:41:46.590 --> 00:41:49.810
Obviously, this concept
comes from classical guitars.

00:41:49.810 --> 00:41:51.650
When people sit down and
play classical guitars,

00:41:51.650 --> 00:41:54.850
they'll place their forearm to
play, which is a proper form

00:41:54.850 --> 00:41:56.840
of interpreting the
classical guitar,

00:41:56.840 --> 00:42:01.060
which is technically not the
same applies to the cuatro.

00:42:01.060 --> 00:42:03.750
A lot of times when we're
playing, it's up here.

00:42:03.750 --> 00:42:05.230
Such a small instrument
to begin with.

00:42:05.230 --> 00:42:06.530
You're up here.

00:42:06.530 --> 00:42:09.690
But sometimes I like to sit down
and interpret my pieces like that.

00:42:09.690 --> 00:42:13.380
So this is something that is
one of his signature things,

00:42:13.380 --> 00:42:15.370 position:56%
on a cuatro he'll place an arm rest.

00:42:15.370 --> 00:42:16.670
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Interesting.

00:42:16.670 --> 00:42:20.920
So getting back to New Jersey a
little bit: Who do you play for?

00:42:20.920 --> 00:42:23.020
Who's the people in the
audience and what are they doing?

00:42:23.020 --> 00:42:24.420
Are they sitting there
listening to you?

00:42:24.420 --> 00:42:25.720
Are they dancing?

00:42:25.720 --> 00:42:27.020
What -- tell us about that.

00:42:27.020 --> 00:42:28.320
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: I guess
that depends on what type

00:42:28.320 --> 00:42:30.080
of venue or event it may be.

00:42:30.080 --> 00:42:35.200
Predominantly, again, it goes
back to what I was saying earlier.

00:42:35.200 --> 00:42:39.170
A lot of people love to
hear the festive stuff.

00:42:39.170 --> 00:42:43.600
People listen to this instrument
and like what you guys head today

00:42:43.600 --> 00:42:45.450
on stage with us performing.

00:42:45.450 --> 00:42:48.300
A lot of it is just danceable
music and people want us to come

00:42:48.300 --> 00:42:53.030
to a party or graduation or
wedding reception and play.

00:42:53.030 --> 00:42:57.040
It makes me -- now that you
mention it, it makes me go back

00:42:57.040 --> 00:43:03.350
to Ladi's days where if there was a
party, people would ask for dansas.

00:43:03.350 --> 00:43:05.680
People would ask for
his compositions.

00:43:05.680 --> 00:43:09.050
That was the danceable music
of that time, the dansas,

00:43:09.050 --> 00:43:13.780
the formal type ballroom dancing,
and mazurkas and valses and things.

00:43:13.780 --> 00:43:15.080
Nowadays, it's different.

00:43:15.080 --> 00:43:19.190
Now with the modern times and all,
this instrument has to try to keep

00:43:19.190 --> 00:43:22.700
up and so with all the different
genres and styles out there,

00:43:22.700 --> 00:43:26.140
now we find ourselves playing a
lot of more of the danceable music.

00:43:26.140 --> 00:43:28.770
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Do you
play any Jimmy Hendrix?

00:43:28.770 --> 00:43:30.950
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: No, actually --

00:43:30.950 --> 00:43:33.570
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: What's some
of the wild stuff you might do?

00:43:33.570 --> 00:43:34.870
Even for fun?

00:43:34.870 --> 00:43:36.170
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: I think
we've experimented with

00:43:36.170 --> 00:43:37.470
"Hotel California" before.

00:43:37.470 --> 00:43:38.770
We've even tried to
experiment and delve

00:43:38.770 --> 00:43:40.070
into the Cuban style music also.

00:43:40.070 --> 00:43:41.370
I get some of my influences from
Cuban style music, the Cuban tres,

00:43:41.370 --> 00:43:42.670
which is their folklore guitar.

00:43:42.670 --> 00:43:44.250
And I try to adapt some
of that to the cuatro.

00:43:44.250 --> 00:43:47.370
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: So
who are the audiences?

00:43:47.370 --> 00:43:50.210
Are they all Boricuas?

00:43:50.210 --> 00:43:52.770
Are they all anybody?

00:43:52.770 --> 00:43:55.890
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: The
majority, yeah.

00:43:55.890 --> 00:44:03.490
Most of the time it is
fellow countrymen and people

00:44:03.490 --> 00:44:10.610
from Puerto Rico that just want to
have our music and such like that.

00:44:10.610 --> 00:44:15.020
We -- I do have to mention -- I
absolutely love the opportunity

00:44:15.020 --> 00:44:18.390
to perform for not Puerto
Ricans, for other cultures,

00:44:18.390 --> 00:44:19.890 position:56%
because it's my opportunity to teach

00:44:19.890 --> 00:44:22.670
about the instrument
and things like that.

00:44:22.670 --> 00:44:27.140
This instrument isn't as popular
as some of us think it is.

00:44:27.140 --> 00:44:29.520
You go to certain areas and
countries within Europe,

00:44:29.520 --> 00:44:31.670
and they've never seen this thing.

00:44:31.670 --> 00:44:34.670
And so I love the chance and
opportunity to say, "hey,

00:44:34.670 --> 00:44:38.120
did you know about this instrument,
where it's from, how it sounds?

00:44:38.120 --> 00:44:42.130
" And maybe try to get them to
kind of follow with the sound.

00:44:42.130 --> 00:44:45.670
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Somebody might
say you must be from -- cuatro --

00:44:45.670 --> 00:44:48.420
that must be from Venezuela
or something like that

00:44:48.420 --> 00:44:52.940
because the famous instrument
there, Colombia or whatever.

00:44:52.940 --> 00:44:56.180
What -- so what -- what's
your neighborhood like?

00:44:56.180 --> 00:44:57.560
Are you in a Puerto
Rican neighborhood or --

00:44:57.560 --> 00:44:59.850
where do you -- what's your -- ?

00:44:59.850 --> 00:45:01.730
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: The city I grew

00:45:01.730 --> 00:45:05.350
up in Trenton is more
of an urban setting.

00:45:05.350 --> 00:45:08.410
There are a lot of minorities.

00:45:08.410 --> 00:45:12.420
A lot of -- I noticed the
past ten, fifteen years,

00:45:12.420 --> 00:45:18.220 position:56%
a lot of Puerto Ricans have migrated
out of Trenton to different areas.

00:45:18.220 --> 00:45:23.150
I have the privilege of knowing
two cuatro players that still stay

00:45:23.150 --> 00:45:27.420
and live in Trenton so we can
get together from time to time,

00:45:27.420 --> 00:45:30.300
kind of share inspiration,
ideas and such.

00:45:30.300 --> 00:45:32.140
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: How do
you fit this into your life?

00:45:32.140 --> 00:45:37.630
Are there other jealousies
out there that want your time?

00:45:37.630 --> 00:45:38.930
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: No.

00:45:38.930 --> 00:45:40.230
Actually, this is it.

00:45:40.230 --> 00:45:41.530
Yeah, this is it....

00:45:41.530 --> 00:45:42.830
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: 24, 7?

00:45:42.830 --> 00:45:44.970
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: I mean, I do have
a full time job, but any moment,

00:45:44.970 --> 00:45:48.290
any breathing moment I can, I'm
sitting down with this thing trying

00:45:48.290 --> 00:45:50.240
to figure out where it's
going to take me next.

00:45:50.240 --> 00:45:53.120
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: What do
you do in your full time job?

00:45:53.120 --> 00:45:54.420
Police officer?

00:45:54.420 --> 00:45:56.610
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: I'm actually a
humane law enforcement officer,

00:45:56.610 --> 00:45:57.910
humane police officer.

00:45:57.910 --> 00:46:00.810
So for the past almost 20 years
I investigate animal cruelty.

00:46:00.810 --> 00:46:03.760
That's something that I've
always been passionate about.

00:46:03.760 --> 00:46:06.440
That's why I've been here so long.

00:46:06.440 --> 00:46:08.210
It's something that I love doing.

00:46:08.210 --> 00:46:12.280
Not anything that I was focusing on
doing, just kind of fell into it,

00:46:12.280 --> 00:46:15.340
but fell in love with it
and been there ever since.

00:46:15.340 --> 00:46:17.550
It's such a rewarding job.

00:46:17.550 --> 00:46:23.640
And so it's kind of
strange because I come home

00:46:23.640 --> 00:46:24.960
and then I sit down with this.

00:46:24.960 --> 00:46:26.450
It's a whole different world.

00:46:26.450 --> 00:46:28.810
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Actually,
one of the reasons I asked is

00:46:28.810 --> 00:46:31.050
because I knew someone
who was a police officer,

00:46:31.050 --> 00:46:35.200
and he was a salsa flutist,
and so he would go shut himself

00:46:35.200 --> 00:46:37.780
in his car and practice it.

00:46:37.780 --> 00:46:39.080
I just wondered if you do the same.

00:46:39.080 --> 00:46:40.380
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Yeah.

00:46:40.380 --> 00:46:44.120
In my earlier years, I would take
my -- one of my lower-end cuatros.

00:46:44.120 --> 00:46:46.200
I didn't want to damage my
good ones, but I would take one

00:46:46.200 --> 00:46:50.560
of my cuatros to work with me to
headquarters and just practice

00:46:50.560 --> 00:46:53.570
because I would have -- I
don't read or write music.

00:46:53.570 --> 00:46:56.440
Everything I do is mostly by ear.

00:46:56.440 --> 00:47:00.390
And so when I would get one of my
inspirations for my compositions

00:47:00.390 --> 00:47:03.450
for example, I have to sing it
all day so I wouldn't forget

00:47:03.450 --> 00:47:06.200
so I would take my cuatro
with me, and I'll play the

00:47:06.200 --> 00:47:09.110
or dansa I'll play the
mazurka over and over and over

00:47:09.110 --> 00:47:11.240
so I won't forget it
on my lunch break,

00:47:11.240 --> 00:47:15.560
and until the song is complete,
it would take me several weeks.

00:47:15.560 --> 00:47:18.900
Sometimes I will start a
composition, leave it alone,

00:47:18.900 --> 00:47:23.040 position:56%
step back and try to listen to it
from afar and wonder what I'm doing.

00:47:23.040 --> 00:47:24.340
Is it going in the right direction?

00:47:24.340 --> 00:47:27.250
Is it going to have the same
inspiration when I'm done?

00:47:27.250 --> 00:47:30.940
So on and so forth until
the piece is complete.

00:47:30.940 --> 00:47:32.240
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Yeah.

00:47:32.240 --> 00:47:34.780
Those two pieces you played have
a beautiful sentimentality to it,

00:47:34.780 --> 00:47:38.190
an elegance to it, well
thought out kind of feel.

00:47:38.190 --> 00:47:39.490
Really nice.

00:47:39.490 --> 00:47:42.610
Has anyone else ever
played your compositions

00:47:42.610 --> 00:47:45.740
or is it too challenging for them?

00:47:45.740 --> 00:47:47.270
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: My pieces
aren't really that complex.

00:47:47.270 --> 00:47:51.200
I mean, they're -- my pieces
are predominantly simple.

00:47:51.200 --> 00:47:54.700
I have heard one or two cuatro
players try to interpret some

00:47:54.700 --> 00:47:57.160
of my songs and ask
if they can play them.

00:47:57.160 --> 00:47:59.000
And by all means, that's
what it's here for.

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:03.970
I'm not picky or -- but I would
say stingy about my pieces.

00:48:03.970 --> 00:48:08.030
Anyone wants to learn my
songs, more power to them.

00:48:08.030 --> 00:48:10.950
It's there for that reason
so it can keep going.

00:48:10.950 --> 00:48:13.600
I want to be able to grow old
and many years later hear one

00:48:13.600 --> 00:48:15.980
of my songs and say I'm
glad that I was able

00:48:15.980 --> 00:48:18.000
to inspire this one
particular person.

00:48:18.000 --> 00:48:20.880 position:56%
Maybe that one song was the one song
that person wanted to hear needed

00:48:20.880 --> 00:48:25.040
to hear to get an inspiration to
continue playing and learning.

00:48:25.040 --> 00:48:27.740
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: On the
topic of growing old,

00:48:27.740 --> 00:48:30.330
we're here in the Library
of Congress.

00:48:30.330 --> 00:48:33.360
And certain institutions
in this town, Washington,

00:48:33.360 --> 00:48:38.480
D.C. think a long time ahead.

00:48:38.480 --> 00:48:41.600
So we're right now -- this
will be part of the archives.

00:48:41.600 --> 00:48:43.640
This is part of the
collections here.

00:48:43.640 --> 00:48:48.060
And I assume it'll be
here for 50, 100, 200,

00:48:48.060 --> 00:48:50.780
whatever hundreds of
years there might be.

00:48:50.780 --> 00:48:53.310
What right now -- do
you have anything

00:48:53.310 --> 00:48:57.390
that you think people should know a
hundred years from now or 200 years

00:48:57.390 --> 00:49:02.240
from now or whatever about your
music, about you, about the group

00:49:02.240 --> 00:49:05.590
or what part of American
society you are?

00:49:05.590 --> 00:49:07.610
No pressure.

00:49:07.610 --> 00:49:10.790 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Not at all, right?

00:49:10.790 --> 00:49:12.090
Not at all.

00:49:12.090 --> 00:49:13.390
Wow.

00:49:13.390 --> 00:49:14.950
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Even if something
frivolous -- whatever it might be.

00:49:14.950 --> 00:49:19.900 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Yeah, I would want
-- obviously, I would want the music

00:49:19.900 --> 00:49:22.930
and the culture of
the music to flourish.

00:49:22.930 --> 00:49:28.600
I'm at a point right now in
this time in era and generation

00:49:28.600 --> 00:49:31.080
where the cuatro has grown a lot.

00:49:31.080 --> 00:49:36.180
It has continued to evolve,
and I'm seeing it grow,

00:49:36.180 --> 00:49:39.750
although in a small community that
it is, I am seeing it growing.

00:49:39.750 --> 00:49:43.460
And I just -- I hope that it
continues and continues to grow.

00:49:43.460 --> 00:49:48.330
It's flourishing very well now,
and I want that to keep on going

00:49:48.330 --> 00:49:53.110
and eventually until the cuatro
is basically fully mainstream

00:49:53.110 --> 00:49:57.430
as it would be - as a
guitar is or a piano.

00:49:57.430 --> 00:50:01.960
I want this instrument to
somehow revolutionize the music

00:50:01.960 --> 00:50:03.610
of Puerto Rico.

00:50:03.610 --> 00:50:06.090
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: Well, they
say that right now what one

00:50:06.090 --> 00:50:09.250
out of six people who live in
the United States are Latino.

00:50:09.250 --> 00:50:14.940
So as the demography moves
ahead, it could in a way happen

00:50:14.940 --> 00:50:19.610
in a very organic sense combined
with beauty of your music

00:50:19.610 --> 00:50:21.760
and also changing demography
of the United States.

00:50:21.760 --> 00:50:23.580
That's the kind of thing
that I think about.

00:50:23.580 --> 00:50:27.830
Who are the Ladis now
for the future?

00:50:27.830 --> 00:50:30.720
Or who are the Lead
Bellys -he was like 1940's,

00:50:30.720 --> 00:50:32.890
the Woodie Guthries
from way back then?

00:50:32.890 --> 00:50:37.130
Looking ahead now, who are
they right now looking today?

00:50:37.130 --> 00:50:38.430
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: Who are they?

00:50:38.430 --> 00:50:39.730
Where are they?

00:50:39.730 --> 00:50:41.030
What are they doing?

00:50:41.030 --> 00:50:42.330
And how will they change
the world as we know it

00:50:42.330 --> 00:50:43.630
when it comes to the cuatro?

00:50:43.630 --> 00:50:44.930
&gt;&gt; Daniel Sheehy: And that's
why we're interviewing you.

00:50:44.930 --> 00:50:52.120
&gt;&gt; Gabriel Muñoz: We can only hope
